Paul,<br>
There you go again, getting us to think. Just when things started to heat up in Nam, you left us, not even a kiss goodbye. Now, there a thread for you, saying goodbye in Nam and to Nam.<br><br>
November, December and Early january were hard months on us, we encountered reinforced NVA forces every which way we turned. <br><br>
By late December and early January we had uprooted their well dug in trenches and fortified hospitals and command centers around Charlie's Ridge and An Hoa. We didn’t know anything about Tet, then guess we were lucky and encountered them before they launched their plans in our area. But, because of this we lost a lot of men but so did the gooks. By the time Tet came around, they were way undermanned, and the few replacements they got in were inexperienced so they were able to launch the plans they had, had for DaNang. <br><br>
In early November, we had eliminated almost all of the VC from our area. Very few of them remained , they had ceased to operate in any notable force. The VC battalions that had been operating,in our area, made a mistake on November 8th and attacked a settlement near us. They were preparing for Tet, and had combined most of their forces for that operation. By a twist of luck we were able to box them in a 2 mile radius. Artillery and air support too out what remained. After that according to all the paper work we captured or found it was all NVA operating in our area.<br><br>
So Tet, for us was somewhat quite, compared to the rest of the area around us, because of this we were on stand by to go out as a reactionary force during Tet. We were also being brought back up to, because of the men we had lost.<br><br>
To answer your question, Did the north think there would be a general uprising? According to history, yes, they believed the civilians would arise to help win the war. But someone forgot to tell the civilians, who opposed the North. The NVA in the field had been led to believe that there would be an uprising, but it was all lies. <br><br>
For us, it was a victory, but the media and politicians back home saw it as a failure.<br>

